The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Down the years
                                                                                                                                                                                                     Down the years
                      
	Born:   
	October 30, 1960 in Lanus. Raised in Villa Fiorito on the southern outskirts of Buenos Aires. Has three elder sisters and two younger brothers  Hugo and Eduardo  both of whom played professional football.   
	Early days:   
	At 11, Maradona joined Argentinos Juniors after he was spotted by a talent scout. A poor boy, Maradona started earning at the age of 12 by displaying his magical ball skills during the half time of first division matches.   
	Club career   
	Oct. 20, 1976: Made his professional debut with Argentinos Juniors. Played only three matches between 1976 and 1981.   
	 1981: Was transferred to Boca Juniors. Won his first league title for Boca Juniors in 1982.   
	 1982: Was transferred to FC Barcelona in Spain for a then world record 5m. In 1983 helped Barcelona win the Copa del Rey beating Real Madrid. Also won the Spanish Super Cup defeating Athletic de Bilbao.   
	 1984: Maradona was transferred to Italian Serie A club Napoli for another record fee of 6.9m. He spent his best years in Napoli.   
	 Titles with Napoli: Maradona won the league titles with Napoli in 1986-87 and 1989-90. Finished runners-up in 1987-88 and 1988-89. Won the Coppa Italia in 1987, secured second place in 1989. Won the Italian Super Cup and UEFA Cup in 1990.   
	 1992: After serving a 15-month ban for cocaine use, Maradona left Napoli in disgrace. Joined Seville (1992-93) but never regained his magical touch.  
	 1993: Played for Newells Old Boys.   
	 1995: Returned to Boca Juniors for two years.   
	International career:  
	 Played four World Cups for Argentina from 1982 to 1994. He won the 1986 World Cup and finished second in 1990. In all, he earned 91 caps for Argentina and scored 34 goals.  
	 Feb. 27, 1977: Made his full international debut against Hungary.   
	 1979: Won the World Youth Championship for Argentina. He was the star of the tournament and played brilliant football in their 3-1 win over Soviet Union in the final.   
	June 2, 1979: Scored his first senior international goal in the 3-1 win against Scotland.   
	1982: Played his first World Cup in Spain. He struck twice against Hungary but was sent off against Brazil for foul play. He played in all the five matches.   
	 1986: Maradonas most memorable year. Led Argentina to victory in the 1986 World Cup in Mexico.   
	 1990: Led Argentina again to reach the World Cup final in Italy before losing to West Germany.   
	 1994: Maradonas last and worst World Cup. He played only two matches, scoring against Greece before being sent home after failing a drug test for ephedrine. Argentina were eliminated in the second round   
	High points:   
	1986: Maradonas second goal against England in the 1986 quarter final against England was to be later voted by Fifa as the greatest goal in the history of the World Cup. He picked the ball in his own half and with 11 touches swivelled around and ran more than half the length of the field, dribbling past five English players  Glenn Hoddle, Peter Reid, Kenny Sansom, Terry Butcher and Terry Fenwick  besides goalkeeper Peter Shilton.   
	 2000: Fifa conducted a fan poll on the Internet, to elect the Player of the Century. Maradona finished at the top with 53.6% of the votes. However, Fifa awarded it to him jointly with Pele.  
	 2002: Maradona won a Fifa poll in which his second goal against England was chosen as the best ever scored in a World Cup.  
	 2003: Argentinos Juniors named its stadium after Maradona.  
	 Low points:   
	Maradona is considered one of the worlds most controversial sporting figures.   
	1986: The biggest controversy in Maradonas life was in the 1986 World Cup when he used his hand to score against England in the quarter finals on June 22. Later he said that the goal was scored by the hand of God.  
	1991: He was suspended from football for 15 months after failing a dope test for cocaine in Italy.   
	 1994: Was sent home from the 1994 World Cup in the US for using ephedrine.   
	 2004: Doctors reported that Maradona had suffered a major heart attack following a cocaine overdose and was admitted to hospital in Buenos Aires. He was discharged 11 days later.   
	 2007: He was readmitted to hospital, released and was readmitted again for hepatitis and alcohol abuse. After transfer to a psychiatric clinic specialising in alcohol-related problems, he was discharged.   COMPILED BY SPORTSDESK                                                                                                                      
